The article is a presidential proclamation by President Barack Obama declaring the third week of July as "Captive Nations Week." This proclamation is in solidarity with those living without personal or political autonomy behind oppressive regimes. The proclamation acknowledges that while many nations have embraced self-governance and basic human rights, there are still regimes that suppress the aspirations of their people through violence, threats, and isolation. The article emphasizes the importance of supporting human rights and democratic values, empowering civil societies, and connecting people through new technologies. The proclamation also references the historical context of the Cold War and the struggles of individuals who fought for freedom and the tearing down of walls. The proclamation concludes by calling upon the people of the United States to reaffirm their commitment to those working for human rights and dignity globally.